The coolest museum I’ve visited so far!😊 - The three cyclists:
Evocative statue of three racing cyclists. The five wheels of the three bicycles form the Olympic symbol
- The Olympic gateway: 
Gate surmounted by the headless figures of a musclebound man and a woman.
- The first Olympic flag created in 1914:
The flag was created for the olympic jubilee congress in 1914 in Paris in celebration of the 20th anniversary of the olympic movement
- Wooden skis: @atakanalaftargil  iyice baktim ama seni  arsiv’de goremedim😅
- The basketball signed by the USA ‘Dream team’ Olympic champion 1992:
Men’s basketball was open for the first time to all professionals which brought about the establishment of the Dream team: Michael Jordan, Earvin Johnson, Larry Bird and Charley Barkley.

HAPPY BIRTHDAY - FELIZ CUMPLEAÑOS TO THE RUTA DE LA AMISTAD - MEXICO 68
Station #10 “Sundial”
Artist: Grzegorz Kowalski (POL) - (1942)
Seven cones of identical dimensions, each one spread out in a different direction and position. The tops of two of them have been cut off, and one has been turned upside down. Constructed from  reinforced concrete and standing five metres high, they are painted in various warm tones, from yellow and orange to red and ochre. Thanks to its position, the central cone is the one that receives the full force of the sun. The conical shapes play off one another, creating a sensation of movement and contradictory forces for spectators passing through the area.

HAPPY BIRTHDAY - FELIZ CUMPLEAÑOS TO THE RUTA DE LA AMISTAD - MEXICO 68
Station #9 / Untitled
Artist: Todd Williams (USA) - (1939)
This seven-metre-high sculpture, made of reinforced concrete, is composed of three elements connected by different circular and oval parts. Together they make up a space, or roof, that offers shelter and allows passage beneath it. The work was originally constructed on a mound of volcanic rock (which is the natural landscape of the area), inside which was the Olympic Village warm-up arena that is still used today.

Station #8 “Solar Disc” 
Artist: Jacques Moeschal (BEL), (1913 - 2004)
This sculpture represents a Maya “sun” symbol, erected on top of the hardened lava flow that covered a 2,000-year-old pyramid built by the Cuicuilco culture. During the Olympic Games, this piece was located at the entrance to the Olympic Village.

I am a HUGE sports and athletics fan so I was absolutely geeking out today at the Olympic Museum. Learning the history of these games and seeing the mementos of my biggest athletic heroes was a truly moving moment for me. The communal spirit of the games, when the world sets aside their differences and converges to witness wonders, is unlike any other that I know. 
In order of appearance:
1. The original Olympic flag

2. Jesse Owens - Berlin 1936 - The Nazi Olympics

3. USA Hockey - Lake Placid 1980 - The Miracle on Ice

4. Usain Bolt - Beijing 2008

5. Michael Phelps - Athens 2004

6. USA Basketball - Barcelona 1992 - The Dream Team

7. Michael Johnson - Atlanta 1996

8. Rafa Nadal - Beijing 2008

9. The Olympic medals

10. The Olympic torches

Artist: Costantino Nivola (ITA), (1911 - 1988)
The reinforced concrete sculpture, 11 metres high, is made up of two geometric bodies one on top of the other. At the summit sits a dove or a hand, depending on the observer’s point of view. The straight lines use the colours of the Italian flag. ·

HAPPY BIRTHDAY - FELIZ CUMPLEAÑOS TO THE RUTA DE LA AMISTAD - MEXICO 68
Station #5 “The Biped Sun”
Artist: Pierre Székely (HUN), (1923 - 2001)
Reinforced concrete indefinite figures standing 13 metres high. The sculpture’s coarse finishing gives it a very organic characteristic that makes it stand out from the rest of the works of art that have a geometric characteristic. In the artist’s words, “Time passes by with nothing to be done about it.  My sculptures are timeless signs of humanity, whose only reason for existing is to give pleasure.”

HAPPY BIRTHDAY - FELIZ CUMPLEAÑOS TO THE RUTA DE LA AMISTAD - MEXICO 68
Station #4 “Sun"
Artist: Kiyoshi Takahashi (JPN), (1925 - 1996)
Made up of 27-metre gigantic white “Suns” made of reinforced concrete.  From the optical illusion caused by the speed of the cars as they drove by on the Periférico, and the use of the spaces described in the sculpture, the artist managed to project the effect of two complete suns rotating around their own centre.

When we were asked to do a documentary about the sport of show jumping, we welcomed the opportunity, even though we didn’t know quite where it would take us at the time.
.
We are so thankful to have been a part of this film …
.
For the opportunity to create something beautiful and experience the sport in a new way,
.
For the opportunity to film, edit, co-produce, and direct, and see this project from start to finish.
.
We are thankful for the awards this film has received, for screenings with our friends, watching them laugh and wipe away tears during the film,
.
And even a screening alongside Olympic athletes at @lakeplacidolympicmuseum .
.
We are thankful for the thousands of hours and edits and re-edits that brought us to this point,
.
And we’re excited to see where else this film will go next!
.
Thanks for being part of this journey, and stay tuned this week for more from the documentary film, Desert Flight.
